Today I wanted to continue this

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:04.000
treatment of covalent compounds.
And specifically I wanted to talk

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
broadly about how we determine state
of aggregation.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
In other words,
how do we determine whether

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
something is going to be a solid or
a liquid or a gas?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
We have already seen that ionic
compounds, by their nature,

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
because they have unsaturated bonds
and they continue to allow more ions

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
to glom onto the initial starting
point results in a large aggregate,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
tightly bound, leads to crystal
formation.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:56.150
The crystal is the regularity,
but definitely solid formation.

00:02:56.150 --> 00:03:00.300
And when you are trying to answer
the question is something a solid or

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:04.460
a liquid or a gas under certain
conditions, this is the subliminal

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:08.610
message. You have to compare the
cohesive forces versus the

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:12.760
disruptive forces.
So the cohesive forces are the

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:16.920
binding forces and the disruptive
forces typically are

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:21.120
thermal in origin.
We have to compare the binding

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:25.370
energy of the substance to the
general thermal energy.

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:29.620
And that is shown here.
Binding energy, then that gets back

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:33.870
to the nature.
If it is an ionic compound,

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:38.120
this binding energy is that Madelung
bearing crystal lattice energy,

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:42.370
and it is very negative. For sodium
chloride it is about 787 kilojoules

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.620
per mole. Whereas,
the thermal energy in this room is

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:50.870
about a 40th of an electron volt.
That is small. Sodium chloride is

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:54.850
a crystal at room temperature.
Now I want to turn to covalent

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:58.570
compounds and ask the same question.
What is the state of aggregation?

00:03:58.570 --> 00:04:02.280
But there is a fork in the road here.
There are two types of covalent

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:05.990
compounds. We saw,
as is shown up here on the slide,

00:04:05.990 --> 00:04:09.710
the results when we have just the
single molecules.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:13.420
But we also saw, at the end of last
lecture, it is also possible to talk

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:17.140
about covalent networks.
We looked at diamond and we looked

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:20.720
at graphite.
Now, in the case of diamond and

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:24.160
graphite, we are in a situation that
is similar to ionic solids.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:27.610
In other words, we have large
aggregates because the sp3

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:31.050
hybridization allows for carbon to
bond to carbon to bond to carbon to

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:34.490
bond to carbon.
And so you end up with a large

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:37.940
aggregate. In fact,
it is an ordered aggregate.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:41.380
It is a crystal. Diamond is a
crystal, just as sodium chloride is

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:44.830
a crystal, but both of them are
large aggregates.

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:48.270
And we saw also that the binding
energy in diamond is

00:04:48.270 --> 00:04:51.870
very, very strong.
Very strongly negative.

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:55.620
And so, therefore, it trumps the
thermal energy of the system.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:59.370
So these are solids at room
temperature. How about molecules?

00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:03.120
That's what I want to focus on
today. What is the nature of

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:06.870
binding in molecular systems?
And specifically let's just take

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:10.620
one of the molecules we looked at
last day. We looked at sulfur

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:14.370
hexafluoride. And I told you,
sulfur hexafluoride is a gas at room

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:18.120
temperature, even though this thing
has a very, very high

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:36.773
molecular weight.
The question we are really asking is

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.000
what are the forces that would cause
sulfur hexafluoride to bind to

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:15.000
itself? And so far what we have
been looking at,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.000
electron domain theory,
doesn't answer this question at all.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Electron domain theory treats what
is going on inside the molecule.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:52.660
It treats intramolecular bonding.
This is between sulfur and fluorine.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:57.990
And this is a very strong reaction
and is referred to as a primary bond

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:03.330
because it is the first bond that
forms. If I look at the world from

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:08.660
the vantage point of sulfur,
the first bond sulfur encounters is

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:13.990
this primary bond to its neighboring
flourines. But now I want to ask

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:19.330
how does this molecule,
which we know is net neutral,

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:25.870
bond to another one like it?
That now means we have to shift,

00:06:25.870 --> 00:06:33.620
so state of aggregation is not
determined by this at all.

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:41.370
State of aggregation is determined
by intermolecular forces.

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:49.120
And they are different. What we
want to do is look at the

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:54.660
intermolecular forces.
And, for that,

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:57.990
we are going to go through this
catalog. That's last day.

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:01.330
This is what we are going to do.
We are going to go through this

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:04.660
catalog. I am going to show you
four different types of

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.990
intermolecular forces,
and I am going to go about them

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:11.330
systematically.
The first one is dipole-dipole

00:07:11.330 --> 00:07:23.660
interactions.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:24.660
And, clearly, this interaction
occurs only between polar molecules.

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:36.986
Involves polar molecules.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:38.220
These molecules have a net dipole
moment. We could model them as

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:42.440
dipoles. And so if this is,
for example, an isolated molecule of

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:46.660
hydrogen chloride,
we know we have a strong covalent

00:07:46.660 --> 00:07:50.880
bond within the molecule and we know
the shape of the molecule.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:55.530
It is linear.
But how does this hydrogen chloride

00:07:55.530 --> 00:08:00.610
bond to another hydrogen chloride?
Well, we can see that this is delta

00:08:00.610 --> 00:08:05.690
minus, this is delta plus,
and so this delta minus end is

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:10.760
attracted to the delta plus end of
an adjacent molecule and so on and

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:15.840
so on. So this is a dipole-dipole
interaction that,

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:20.920
when the temperature is low enough,
the thermal energy will not disrupt

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:39.840
the bonds that are forming by this
dipole-dipole interaction.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:31.270
So it is operative at low
temperature. And these are all weak

00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:36.540
interactions. Everything I am going
to talk about today is weak by an

00:08:36.540 --> 00:08:41.810
order of magnitude in comparison to
the primary reactions.

00:08:41.810 --> 00:08:47.080
If we compare ionic bonding and
primary covalent bonding with this

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:52.360
sort of thing,
this is down at around on the order

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:56.710
of about 10 kilojoules per mole.
Whereas, up here we are talking

00:08:56.710 --> 00:09:00.140
about hundreds of kilojoules per
mole. These are very weak,

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:03.570
which means that at room temperature
HCl is a gas, sodium chloride and

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:06.990
diamond are solids.
And the energy in a dipole-dipole

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:10.420
interaction, I am not going to give
you the full formula,

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:13.850
but I will just give you what it is
proportional to.

00:09:13.850 --> 00:09:17.280
Clearly, it is going to be
proportional to the strength

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:21.390
of the dipole.
Stronger dipoles will bond more

00:09:21.390 --> 00:09:26.190
tightly than weaker dipoles.
And, in fact, it goes as the fourth

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:30.990
power of the dipole moment.
If mu is the dipole moment,

00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:35.790
stronger dipole moments give much,
much stronger interactions than

00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:40.590
weaker dipole moments.
And a dipole moment is proportional

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:45.390
to what? It is proportional to the
charge and the separation.

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:50.190
If I have more charge separated by
a greater distance,

00:09:50.190 --> 00:10:09.246
I construct a greater dipole,
a dipole of greater strength.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:10:00.550
And in the denominator we have the
cube root of the interdipole

00:10:00.550 --> 00:10:06.110
separation. Really,
what we want is very strong dipoles

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:11.660
spaced closely together to give us
the strongest reaction.

00:10:11.660 --> 00:10:17.220
The example HCl, I have used this
in some of my own research.

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:23.390
This thing has a melting point --
HCl has a melting point minus 115

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:30.190
degrees C, and the boiling point at
atmospheric pressure is minus 85

00:10:30.190 --> 00:10:36.990
degrees C. If we go down below
minus 115 degrees,

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:43.790
see, the thermal energy is low
enough that at temperatures below

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:50.590
this value this weak interaction
dominates and we have solid HCl.

00:10:50.590 --> 00:10:55.660
Second form of interaction --
And these are all cataloged in

00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:58.990
Chapter 8 of your book,
this one here is a little bit

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:02.330
premature, but all the books do it
so I will just,

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:05.660
for completeness,
go through it. It is really

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.990
involving solutions.
This one was HCl to HCl.

00:11:08.990 --> 00:11:12.330
It is answering the question under
what circumstances is HCl,

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:15.660
solid, liquid or gas? This one here
is called dipole-induced dipole.

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:18.990
This is really two different
species. You can see in the cartoon

00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:22.330
that the left has HCl,
hydrogen chloride, and the right has

00:11:22.330 --> 00:11:41.060
argon.
So this is bonding between two

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.000
different types of species.
For example, if I were to mix HCl,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
which a gas at room temperature.
Argon is a gas at room temperature.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
I mix two gases at room temperature,
I have a gas. But at low enough

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.000
temperatures, I will get a liquid.
And, at low enough temperatures yet,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
I will get a solid.
It will be essentially a solid

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
alloy of HCl molecules
and argon atoms.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:55.450
What holds that together?
Whenever you see a solid,

00:11:55.450 --> 00:12:00.900
you must conclude that there are
forces that bind the species

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:06.360
together. Things don't just sit
there because they are lazy.

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:11.810
They are bound. What are the
forces that could bind a condensed

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:17.270
form of argon and HCl together?
And the answer is dipole-induced

00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:23.440
dipole interactions.
This is a bit of a departure,

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:30.330
but it will come in handy in a
little bit. This is present in

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:37.220
solutions of what?
You need one polar and nonpolar

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:44.110
species. They could be atoms or
they could be molecules,

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:59.886
it doesn't matter. So how does this
work?

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:56.570
Well, here is the nonpolar molecule.
This is argon, helium or one such

00:12:56.570 --> 00:13:02.140
methane. Nonpolar.
So it has uniform distribution,

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:07.710
by definition. If it is nonpolar
there is no net dipole.

00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:13.280
Here is the nonpolar entity,
nonpolar species. If I bring up a

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:18.850
dipole in close proximity,
what can happen is the following.

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:24.420
This negative end of the dipole
interacts with the electron cloud in

00:13:24.420 --> 00:13:41.840
the nonpolar species so
as to cause repulsion.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:33.830
This cloud, it's in motion,
the electrons are not potted,

00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:37.660
and so the presence of this negative
end of the dipole actually causes

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:41.490
the electrons to flee.
We get a maldistribution in the

00:13:41.490 --> 00:13:45.330
electrons. And,
in fact, this end becomes a little

00:13:45.330 --> 00:13:49.160
bit electron lean,
electron deficient,

00:13:49.160 --> 00:14:07.920
and the other end becomes electron
rich.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.500
What started off minding its own
business with this symmetric

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:42.000
distribution of electrons in the
presence of the dipole takes on a

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.500
dipole moment itself.
So this dipole is induced by the

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:51.000
presence of the permanent dipole.
And now we have some bonding. This

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.500
negative end here now is in a
position to be attracted to the

00:13:55.500 --> 00:14:00.000
positive end of a permanent dipole
and so on and so on.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:25.330
This is how the system operates.
And we know that the energy of the

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:30.660
dipole-induced dipole interaction
goes as one over the square of the

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:35.990
interpolar separation.
This is one over the square of the

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:41.330
interpolar separation.
Whereas, here it is one over the

00:14:41.330 --> 00:14:46.660
cube of the interpolar separation.
And, furthermore, we can talk about

00:14:46.660 --> 00:15:04.386
how susceptible elements
are to this induction.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:56.300
I can give you two different
elements. Suppose I have argon,

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:00.610
and next to it I will put helium.
They both have inert gas electron

00:15:00.610 --> 00:15:04.920
configurations,
but helium is small and has a few

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:09.230
electrons. Argon is large and has
many electrons.

00:15:09.230 --> 00:15:13.530
Which of these two,
argon or helium is more susceptible

00:15:13.530 --> 00:15:17.840
to this electron displacement?
You see that it is argon because

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:23.110
argon is larger. It's squishier.
It is softer. This is hard.

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:29.330
This is like a baseball. This is
like a Nerf ball.

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:35.550
It can be easily distorted in terms
of its charge.

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:41.770
And we call this distortion of
electrical charge polarization.

00:15:41.770 --> 00:16:00.073
Polarization is the official term
for electrical charge displacement.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And so we can quantify the ease with
which electrons are displaced within

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:44.000
a chemical entity by a quantity
called polarizability.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:52.000
And give it the symbol alpha.
And this is a measure of ease of

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:00.000
electron displacement.
And, clearly, polarizability is

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:25.790
affected by --
Now watch the fonts here.

00:16:25.790 --> 00:16:29.390
This is alpha. And then I want to
say alpha is proportional to,

00:16:29.390 --> 00:16:32.990
I don't know how you differentiate
the two. Alpha is proportional to

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:36.590
the number of electrons.
In other words, the more electrons

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:40.190
the more there are to move.
If I only have a couple of

00:16:40.190 --> 00:16:43.790
electrons and I have a couple of
protons, those electrons are more

00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:47.390
tightly bound.
They are less flexible.

00:16:47.390 --> 00:17:06.713
So the number of electrons and also
the size.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:36.000
For equal numbers of electrons,
a larger entity will be softer and

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:41.000
squishier than a smaller entity.
So polarizability scales with

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:46.000
electron number and with size.
We reason that helium is going to

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:51.000
be low polarizability.
Whereas, argon will be high

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:56.000
polarizability.
Because we have a lot of electrons,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:01.000
they have to, by necessity, you know
what the filling sequence is.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:25.140
The more electrons you have,
those last electrons are farther out,

00:17:25.140 --> 00:17:29.280
so the positive charge in the
nucleus has a weaker hold on them.

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:33.420
Therefore, while they are bound,
they are a little bit friskier.

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:37.560
They don't sit in their place.
They move around.

00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:41.710
Now, let's get back to homonuclear
species. This is induced

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:45.850
dipole-induced dipole.
That is the third type of

00:17:45.850 --> 00:18:04.500
interaction. Induced dipole-induced
dipole.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:56.440
This is a really fascinating one.
It puzzled people for a long time.

00:17:56.440 --> 00:18:02.880
And it is dominant in nonpolar
molecules. Dominant in nonpolar

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:09.330
everything. It is dominant in
nonpolar species,

00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:15.770
atoms and molecules.
And here are some examples.

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:21.060
Let's go back. Here is argon.
Now, if you look on your Periodic

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:25.190
Table, argon has a melting point of
84 Kelvin. And it has a boiling

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:29.330
point of 87 Kelvin.
And I told you, whenever you see a

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:33.460
solid, that you have to conclude
that it is held together by some

00:18:33.460 --> 00:18:37.590
force. Let's imagine that we are at
liquid nitrogen temperature.

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:41.730
We take some argon out of an argon
gas cylinder and we flow it through

00:18:41.730 --> 00:18:45.860
a tube. And that tube is immersed
in liquid nitrogen.

00:18:45.860 --> 00:19:05.186
Liquid nitrogen is 77 Kelvin.
Well, that is below 84.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:55.160
The argon is going to solidify.
It is going to deposit on the walls

00:18:55.160 --> 00:19:00.330
of the tube. And after a while I
will have argon ice.

00:19:00.330 --> 00:19:05.490
I am sitting there and looking at
argon ice. What binds argon to

00:19:05.490 --> 00:19:10.660
argon? Well, it is not ionic.
It is not primary covalent. It is

