hydrogen selenide, hydrogen sulfide

00:36:57.620 --> 00:37:01.370
fitting the pattern.
Smaller molecules, lower

00:37:01.370 --> 00:37:05.120
polarizability,
smaller dipole moments,

00:37:05.120 --> 00:37:08.870
everything is fine. Then we get to
H2O and it is up at 100 degrees C

00:37:08.870 --> 00:37:12.620
which is higher than even hydrogen
telluride. Why?

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:16.370
Because the hydrogen bonding is
present in water.

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:20.120
It is not present in the compounds
of hydrogen and any of the other

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:24.230
members of this homologous series.
If it were not for hydrogen bonding,

00:37:24.230 --> 00:37:28.690
water would not boil at 100 degrees
C, it would not melt at zero degrees

00:37:28.690 --> 00:37:33.150
C, and this conversation would take
on a very different character.

00:37:33.150 --> 00:37:37.610
We wouldn't exist. So we need
hydrogen bonding.

00:37:37.610 --> 00:37:42.070
Lastly, let's look at HI.
This is Group 17. These are just

00:37:42.070 --> 00:37:46.530
simple linear molecules.
Hydrogen iodide, hydrogen bromide,

00:37:46.530 --> 00:38:06.193
hydrogen chloride. There is our
prototypical hydrogen chloride.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
We are just getting bigger and
bigger dipoles,

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
higher and higher boiling points.
Finally, we get down to HF which

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:43.000
should be the tiniest.
It should have the weakest

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:47.000
interaction. And we have a very,
very abnormally high boiling point

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:51.000
because hydrogen bonding is
operative. You can see hydrogen

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:55.000
bonding and the impact that it has
on boiling point and properties.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:59.000
And we will return to this when we
talk about conformality in polymers,

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:23.070
in nylons in particular.
And certainly when we get to

00:38:23.070 --> 00:38:27.210
biochemistry because our proteins
consist of, among other things,

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:31.350
hydrogen and oxygen and nitrogen.
And those hydrogen bonds help hold

00:38:31.350 --> 00:38:35.490
the system together.
At this point, just to summarize,

00:38:35.490 --> 00:38:39.640
we have seen three types of primary
bonding. We have seen ionic bonding,

00:38:39.640 --> 00:38:43.780
covalent bonding and,
in certain instances, Van der Waals

00:38:43.780 --> 00:38:47.920
bonding. And things seem to be
working fairly well, but

00:38:47.920 --> 00:39:07.306
then there is data.
And here is some data that I want

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:36.000
you to look at.
These are data of electrical

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.000
conductivity. And up here we have
metals, silver at 10 to the 7th

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:44.000
Siemens per centimeter,
copper at 10 to the 7th Siemens per

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:48.000
centimeter. I mentioned last day
that graphite has some delocalized

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:52.000
electrons. It is 10 to the 4th
Siemens per centimeter.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:56.000
And then we get down to the
insulators. I said diamond was a

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:00.000
good insulator. It is
10 to the minus 11th.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:24.280
There is aluminum oxide,
a good ionic compound. And here is

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:28.570
PTFE, Teflon, 10 to the minus 16th.
The first thing that you notice is

00:39:28.570 --> 00:39:32.850
look at the range.
I mean if you look at the range on

00:39:32.850 --> 00:39:37.140
the Periodic Table,
look at the range of something like

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:41.420
density. Lithium has a density of 0.
3, and you have osmium that is

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:45.710
around 22. It is a range of about
40. Look at this.

00:39:45.710 --> 00:40:05.553
10 to the 7th, 10 to the minus 16th.
A range of 10 to the 23rd.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:53.330
Secondly, what do we know about the
compounds we have seen so far?

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:56.660
Ionic compounds, conductors or
insulators? We know they are

00:39:56.660 --> 00:39:59.990
insulators. They have tightly bond
electrons in stable octet

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:03.320
configurations,
so that is not going to help us.

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:06.660
Covalent compounds. Well, the
network ones are like diamond,

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:09.990
very, very good insulators. Van der
Waals compounds,

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:13.330
let's look at that.
How about argon? Do you think

00:40:13.330 --> 00:40:16.660
argon is going to be a good
conductor of electrons?

00:40:16.660 --> 00:40:35.853
No way. It has inert gas
configuration.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:24.280
Those are the three types of primary
bonding. And I cannot explain how

00:40:24.280 --> 00:40:28.570
three-quarters of the Periodic Table
has this abnormally high value of

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:32.850
electrical conductivity.
It sounds to me like we need to

00:40:32.850 --> 00:40:37.140
come up with yet another form of
bonding. And the answer is metallic

00:40:37.140 --> 00:40:41.420
bonding. Why is it metallic bonding?
Because it is practiced in metals.

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:45.710
Let's look at metallic bonding.
The need for metallic bonding was

00:40:45.710 --> 00:41:05.153
brought on by the observation of
electrical conductivity.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:37.500
If we are going to be true to form
in 3.091, we have to look at the

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:45.000
electronic structure.
And the first model that attempted

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:52.500
to account for the high observed
value of electrical conductivity was

00:40:52.500 --> 00:41:00.000
enunciated in 1900 by a German
physicist by the name of Paul Drude.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:28.570
What he said was he could model a
metal as a mixture of positive

00:41:28.570 --> 00:41:37.140
nuclei plus the inner shell
electrons, which he called this

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:45.710
whole mix of the positive nuclei and
all the inner shell electrons,

00:41:45.710 --> 00:41:52.720
he called that the atomic core.
And then the valence electrons,

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:58.180
he said, were separate. You have
the atomic core plus valence

00:41:58.180 --> 00:42:03.630
electrons which he assumed were free.
That is to say they could move

00:42:03.630 --> 00:42:09.080
about the material.
In other words, they were not

00:42:09.080 --> 00:42:14.540
associated with any single atom.
We call them delocalized. I think

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:31.480
last day I used the
term delocalized.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:25.800
And we will come back to that in a
bit. This is,

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:31.590
in essence, modeling the metal as a
solid consisting of cores and the

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:37.390
electrons freely moving,
much in the same way as a gas.

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:43.190
This was termed the free electron
gas model. In other words,

00:42:43.190 --> 00:43:01.380
a gas of free electrons. And with
this they had some success.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:53.130
They were able to account for such
things as the heat capacity of

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:57.260
solids. The heat capacity of solids
they could model.

00:42:57.260 --> 00:43:01.390
That was good. And I think there
was something else they were able to

00:43:01.390 --> 00:43:05.530
do. But, by and large,
this did not stand up because it was

00:43:05.530 --> 00:43:09.660
not quantitative.
If it is not quantitative,

00:43:09.660 --> 00:43:13.790
what does that mean right off the
bat? No Nobel prize.

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:17.930
You got it. No Nobel prize for
Paul Drude. No quantitative,

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:22.570
no Nobel prize.
We will just put this here.

00:43:22.570 --> 00:43:27.710
"No Nobel." And it is true.
The people that made really

00:43:27.710 --> 00:43:32.850
important insights but they were not
quantitative, no Nobel.

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:37.990
So it is not quantitative because
it cannot be tested.

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:43.140
And the second thing is it was not
discriminating.

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:48.280
In other words,
if you said assume that something is

00:43:48.280 --> 00:43:53.420
metallic, then you continue with the
atomic core and the gas

00:43:53.420 --> 00:43:58.250
of free electrons.
But that is like saying silver is a

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:02.750
metal and this is how a metal
behaves. But what about the earlier

00:44:02.750 --> 00:44:07.250
question? Why is silver a metal and
diamond not acting as a metal?

00:44:07.250 --> 00:44:11.750
Doesn't diamond have a set of
positive nuclei with inner shell

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:16.250
electrons? Why do you choose to
have the valence electrons of silver

00:44:16.250 --> 00:44:20.750
moving around but the valence
electrons of diamond

00:44:20.750 --> 00:44:25.410
not moving around?
Well, we know a little bit that he

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:30.240
didn't know because we have the
benefit of Linus Pauling and the

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:35.080
understanding of covalent bonding.
But, even so, he could not help

00:44:35.080 --> 00:44:39.910
classify insulators and metals.
And so that did not work. We had

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:44.740
to wait almost 30 years for the next
installment. And so when we return

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:49.580
next day we will look at the next
installment of the attempt to

00:44:49.580 --> 00:44:54.150
explain metallic bonding.
And what happens in the 30 years

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:58.460
between 1900 and 1930?
The quantum revolution.

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:02.760
Clearly, in 1900, in respect of
Professor Drude,

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:07.070
absent quantum mechanics,
there was not much else they could

00:45:07.070 --> 00:45:11.380
have done. But the next people are
going to stand on the shoulders of

00:45:11.380 --> 00:45:15.690
people who gave us quantum mechanics
and explain why we have metals as we

00:45:15.690 --> 00:45:34.913
do. Let's take a look at a few
things before we leave.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:23.850
The unit of conductivity is the
Siemens named after Charles Williams

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:27.710
Siemens who was quite an inventor.
He was born in Germany but spent

00:45:27.710 --> 00:45:31.560
most of his life in the UK.
He gave us the open-hearth furnace

00:45:31.560 --> 00:45:35.420
which dominated steel-making for a
century, laid the first

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:39.280
trans-Atlantic telegraphy cable in
1985, and something dear to my heart

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:43.140
was an early proponent of electric
traction for automobiles,

00:45:43.140 --> 00:46:02.346
no internal combustion engine.
Siemens is this.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:31.000
And so the unit of Siemens is the
reciprocal of the ohm,

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:35.000
which when I was your age actually
was called the mho.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:39.000
That is ohm spelled backwards.
This is electrical engineering.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:43.000
That is supposed to be funny, but
obviously the SI commission decided

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:47.000
mho just does not cut it.
We are going to give it a proper

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:51.000
name with a proper recognition.
And, oddly enough, Ohm, whose unit

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:55.000
is the reciprocal of the Siemens,
was also a professor in Germany.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:19.470
But, when he enunciated his law in
1827, the linearity between

00:46:19.470 --> 00:46:23.940
resistance and the voltage required
to drive a particular current,

00:46:23.940 --> 00:46:28.410
he was so badly ridiculed at his
university that he resigned his

00:46:28.410 --> 00:46:32.880
position. As I told you in the past,
scientific change does not come

00:46:32.880 --> 00:46:37.350
easily. I know Professor Ballinger
talked to you a little bit about

00:46:37.350 --> 00:46:41.820
Midgley. I want to talk to you
about one other invention of

00:46:41.820 --> 00:46:46.290
Midgley's and refer back to all of
these shapes of molecules.

00:46:46.290 --> 00:46:50.760
I call him sp3 Midgley because most
of his work that we know today

00:46:50.760 --> 00:47:10.786
involved sp3 hybridized molecules.
And I know Professor Ballinger

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:39.000
talked about Freon which was a
refrigerant. Midgley at one point

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:43.000
joined the Dayton Engineering
Company, which is DELCO,

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:47.000
which eventually was bought by
General Motors.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:51.000
And in 1921 he discovered this
anti-knock agent for gasoline called

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:55.000
tetraethyl lead.
You know the structure is 6s2p2.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:59.000
You can hybridize this to give us
6sp3. And there are four unpaired

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:23.130
electrons there.
And then we can take the ethyl

00:47:23.130 --> 00:47:27.390
radical and put four of those on.
And so this gets diluted in the

00:47:27.390 --> 00:47:31.660
gasoline and goes through the
combustion process.

00:47:31.660 --> 00:47:35.930
And what it does is actually
reduces the potency of gasoline.

00:47:35.930 --> 00:47:40.190
If the potency of gasoline is too
high, when the fuel first goes into

00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:44.460
the combustion chamber and then the
piston compresses,

00:47:44.460 --> 00:47:48.730
remember everything is hot from the
previous combustion,

00:47:48.730 --> 00:48:07.326
the chamber could explode of its own
accord.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:57.130
And, if it does so,
it with ram the piston up.

00:47:57.130 --> 00:48:01.260
Everything is supposed to be moving
synchronously.

00:48:01.260 --> 00:48:05.390
What you want to do is put
something in the gasoline to delay

00:48:05.390 --> 00:48:09.530
the combustion until the spark plug
fires. The sad thing is that there

00:48:09.530 --> 00:48:13.660
was a superior chemical known
already back in 1920 which was ethyl

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:17.790
alcohol. If ethyl alcohol had been
used, we wouldn't have all the lead

00:48:17.790 --> 00:48:21.930
in the environment that we have
thanks to the use of leaded gasoline

00:48:21.930 --> 00:48:26.080
for about 50 years.
Anyway. This is tetraethyl lead,

00:48:26.080 --> 00:48:30.240
and this was an invention of Midgley.
Now, in the 1970s along came

00:48:30.240 --> 00:48:34.410
catalytic converters which we have
to this day. And these are precious

00:48:34.410 --> 00:48:38.580
metal catalysts,
platinum, palladium and rhodium.

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:42.740
But when tetraethyl lead burns the
carbon forms CO2,

00:48:42.740 --> 00:48:46.910
the hydrogen forms H2O and the lead
forms lead dioxide. And lead

00:48:46.910 --> 00:48:50.850
dioxide is volatile.
And it goes with the exhaust gases.

00:48:50.850 --> 00:48:54.570
And it will pass over the catalyst.
And the catalyst's job is to break

00:48:54.570 --> 00:48:58.280
bonds. And so it breaks the
lead-oxygen bond and reduces it to

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:01.990
lead. And now the lead alloy is
with the catalyst.

00:49:01.990 --> 00:49:05.710
Now you have platinum alloying with
lead. What do you think the

00:49:05.710 --> 00:49:09.420
catalytic activity of lead is?
Considering the difference in cost,

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:13.140
I am willing to wager that if lead
had any catalytic value we wouldn't

00:49:13.140 --> 00:49:17.120
be using platinum.
So when the lead alloys with the

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:21.370
catalyst, it poisons the catalyst.
Hence in the â70s the advent of

00:49:21.370 --> 00:49:25.620
lead-free fuel.
All of these things came together

00:49:25.620 --> 00:49:29.870
as a result of the need to deal with
the absence of the tetraethyl lead

00:49:29.870 --> 00:49:34.120
necessitated by the onset of
catalytic converters.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:38.370
Again you see where the sp3
hybridization comes into play in a

00:49:38.370 --> 00:49:42.620
chemical that was used for about two
generations. When it came along,

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:46.870
people thought it was fantastic to
stabilize internal combustion

00:49:46.870 --> 00:49:51.250
engines.
In the end it was dismissed for its

00:49:51.250 --> 00:49:55.750
toxicity to the environment.
The same thing happened with Freon

00:49:55.750 --> 00:50:00.250
12, dismissed after two generations
for its toxicity to the environment.

